\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.1}{\ignorespaces Illustration of the properties of Bessel beams. (a) The phase fronts of the beam exhibit a helical structure, spiraling around the central axis. (b) A Bessel beam is generated through the superposition of circularly polarized plane waves, with wave vectors $\mathbf {k}$ distributed on a conical surface defined by the angle $\mitvartheta _k = \arctan (\mitvarkappa /k_z)$. (c) The transverse intensity distribution of a Bessel beam displays a central null intensity at the beam axis ($x = y = 0$) and an infinite series of concentric rings. The intensity profile is normalized to the maximum intensity for a beam with parameters $\mitlambda = 800\, \text {nm}$, $\mitvartheta _k = 20^\circ $, $\mitLambda = +1$, and $m_{\mitgamma } = 2$.}}{18}{figure.caption.5}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2.2}{\ignorespaces Time-domain representation of the total vector potential \( \symbf {A}(t) \) for a circularly polarized plane wave laser pulse is shown in the left panels, while in the right panel its corresponding frequency-domain representation, \( [\symcal {F}(\symbf {A})](\mitomega ) \). The plots include laser pulses with durations of two (red), four (blue), and eight (green) optical cycles, with a carrier-envelope phase of \( \mitvarphi _{\mathrm {cep}} = 0 \) and a wavelength of 800 nm. The right panelâ€™s vertical axis represents the absolute amplitude of the vector potential at a peak intensity of \( 5 \times 10^{14} \) W/cm\(^2\).}}{21}{figure.caption.6}%
