\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces The standard contour in complex time describes the electron dynamics, starting from the complex ionization instant~$t_s$, evolving toward its real component~$t_r = \Re (t_s)$, and subsequently propagating along the real-time axis until detection at $t_f \to +\infty $.}}{43}{figure.caption.8}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces 3D Landscape of the time-dependent action $S(t')$ and it projection computed numerically for the strong-field ionization. Height map shows $\Im [S(t')]$ controlling the amplitude $|e^{-iS(t')}| = e^{\Im [S(t')]}$ of the quantum mechanical phase factor. Black curves depict steepest descent contours where $\Re [S(t')] = \mathrm {const.}$, orthogonal to the $\Im [S(t')]$ gradient. Black markers indicate saddle points $t_s$ satisfying $S'(t_s)=0$, which dominate the temporal integration path. The plotted solution corresponds to field parameters: $\mitepsilon = 1.0$, $\mitlambda = 800$ nm, $I = 5 \times 10^{14}$ W/cm$^{2}$, $n_p = 2$ cycles, $I_p = 15.6$ eV. }}{43}{figure.caption.9}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.3}{\ignorespaces Real part of the Volkov phase, $\Re [e^{i S(\mathbf {p},t)}]$, as a function of real time, exhibiting rapid oscillations. The calculation assumes a photoelectron energy $\mitepsilon _p = 5\mitomega $ in a circularly polarized, 8-cycle laser pulse with a peak intensity of $5 \times 10^{14}~\text {W/cm}^2$ and a wavelength of 800~nm. }}{45}{figure.caption.10}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.4}{\ignorespaces Convergence paths of Newton-Raphson iterations in the complex time plane for saddle point solutions. Markers show the progression of iterations (small dots) with final converged saddle points indicated by black circles. The paths represent solutions to the saddle point equation $f(t_s; \mathbf {p}) = 0$ where $\Re (t) \in (0,T_p)$ and $\Im (t) > 0$. Numbers indicate the iteration count for each convergence path. The other parameters are same as in Fig. \ref {fig:Landscape}. }}{51}{figure.caption.11}%
